          <h3>What's more important: 4K resolution or frame rate?</h3>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>
            For YouTube, 4K 30p is the sweet spot. It looks sharp on modern displays 
            and is easy to edit. 4K 60p is useful if you create slow-motion content 
            or want extra-smooth motion. Most viewers won't notice the difference 
            between 30p and 60p for talking-head content.
          </p>
          <p>
            Prioritize good autofocus and stabilization over chasing higher frame rates.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>
          <h3>Do I need full-frame or is APS-C enough?</h3>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>
            APS-C is sufficient for 95% of YouTubers. Full-frame advantages: (1) Better 
            low-light performance, (2) Shallower depth of field for cinematic look, 
            (3) Wider field of view with same lens. But full-frame cameras and lenses 
            cost significantly more.
          </p>
          <p>
            Start with APS-C (Sony ZV-E10 II, Canon R50). Upgrade to full-frame 
            (Canon R8, Sony ZV-E1) when low-light or aesthetic becomes limiting.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

